		"type": "thesis",
		"abstract": "An examination of the relationship between the use of Role-Playing Games and academic engagement and self-efficacy as indicators of academic achievement in high school students at a school in Eastern Canada (n= 29) was undertaken. Research was centred around the question: to what extent has the non-institutionalized use of Role-Playing Games affected students' academic engagement and self-efficacy? This research was undertaken in order to investigate potential uses of the Role-Playing Game as an instructional tool. Mixed-methods research was employed, involving surveys regarding the amount of games played, student interviews, and teacher interviews. It was found that RPG use and self-efficacy were significantly positively correlated, RPG use and academic engagement were weakly to moderately negatively correlated, and that RPG use did not significantly impact the desire to learn. Recurring responses to interviews cited interactivity and ownership of narrative as factors contributing to RPG use by students.",
