		"type": "article-journal",
		"abstract": "Dungeons & Dragons (D&D) is often described as a childhood game of “Cops & Robbers,” but with rules to settle the inevitable “I shot you first ! ” This article considers the implications of adding rationalized rules to imaginative play for understanding the relationship between disenchantment and (re)enchantment in the modern world, as demonstrated in the history of Dungeons & Dragons . It is a history only in a limited sense of the term. It focuses on origins, believing that what Tocqueville said of nations is also true of cultural phenomena such as games: “[T]hey all bear some marks of their origin; and the circumstances which accompanied their birth and contributed to their rise affect the whole term of their being” (Tocqueville 17). Dungeons and Dragons is primarily considered in terms of Max Weber’s discussion of the protestant ethic and the irrationality of rationality; concurrently, this article also demonstrates the utility of D&D as a means to explore any number of cultural and social questions. The productive tension between rationality and enchantment identified in D&D has broad-reaching implications for understanding other areas of culture to which Weberian ideas are more typically applied.",
