		"id": "http://zotero.org/groups/446523/items/Y64CUFKQ",
		"type": "chapter",
		"abstract": "In the old role-play game of Dungeons and Dragons, one rolls the dice to determine the character traits of one’s game avatar. One of the character trait rolls determines whether the avatar is Lawful (in the sense of rule-bound, consistent, and predictable) or Chaotic (in the sense of unruly, unpredictable, or inconsistent). A separate roll determines whether the avatar is Good, Evil, or Neutral. Thus, in the game, characters not only can be “lawful and good,” or “chaotic and evil,” but also “lawful and evil” or “chaotic and good.” From the usual jurisprudential standpoint, both the “lawful evil” and the “chaotic good” seem oxymoronic. We usually think that consistency and goodness go together. As Lon Fuller put it, “I shall have to rest on the assertion of a belief that may seem naïve, namely, that coherence and goodness have more affinity than coherence and evil.” From Kant’s universal principles of reason, to John Rawls’ operationalizing of Kant in his theory of the “original position,” which “generalizes and carries to a higher level of abstraction the familiar theory of the social contract,” to Ronald Dworkin’s “law as integrity” thesis that prefers the coherent interpretation to the incoherent - main-line legal theorists agree that good government ought to be coherent (lawful) and should not make ungeneralizable, un-rule-bound (chaotic) exceptions. In short, lawfulness is at least an aspect of good; unruliness is at least an aspect of evil. Political theorists have made similar points. Hannah Arendt and Lon Fuller point to Nazi Germany’s lawless use of retroactive legislation and its chaotic, opaque, and unpredictable lines of authority as essential means by which Hitler fostered fear and maintained personal control. On the other hand, the Dungeons and Dragons categories suggest that the association of lawfulness with goodness is not a logical necessity. Dolores Umbridge, Darth Vader, General Zod, and the Mayor of Pleasantville are among the classic “lawful evil” characters; Hans Solo, Captain Kirk, Robin Hood, and Mary Poppins are among the classic “chaotic good” characters.",
