		"abstract": "Scope of Study. Among deficits previously identified by researchers working with students served through special education are delays in oral language development and greater externalization in locus of control, a construct of personality. This study investigates the effects of simulation game play upon remediation of these deficit areas. Participating in the study were 26 mildly handicapped adolescents. The experimental group, consisting of 13 students, played Dungeons and Dragons, a fantasy-based role-playing game, during 18 sessions. All participants were administered individual tests utilizing the Utah Test of Language Development, Revised Edition and the Intellectual Achievement Responsibility Questionnaire after the final session of play.\nFindings and Conclusions. One-way analysis of variance tests using the difference between the group means on (1) oral language development and (2) internal versus external locus of control was applied. A significant difference was found to exist at the .05 level in oral language development. A significant difference was found to exist at the .05 level in internalization of locus of control. These findings tend to support the contention that a simulation game format is a viable remediation tool when used with mildly handicapped adolescents. Further, these findings support past research findings with both disabled and nondisabled participants.",
