		"type": "article-journal",
		"abstract": "This qualitative study aimed to describe player experiences from playing Dungeons & Dragons. Research\nquestions sought to identify which experiences were meaningful, beneficial, and appealing about the game.\nThrough purposive non-random sampling, a total of 60 respondents answered the survey between June and\nAugust 2016. Majority of respondents were male, within the age range of 25 - 34 years, and having at least 1 -\n3 years of experience. Thematic analysis was used to categorize the data acquired through an online survey.\nThe researcher categorized keywords into three core elements: Creative, Emotional, and Social Experiences.\nThe findings show that there is no doubt role-playing games such as D&D have the potential to entertain, heal,\nand educate. Psychological implications include D&D and TRPGs alike to be used in both therapeutic and\neducational settings. When designed thoughtfully and facilitated carefully, RPGs can help clients understand\nthemselves on a deeper level, or discover something new about them. Even for regular players, RPGs can be a\nplayground to exercise social and cognitive skills.",
