		"type": "paper-conference",
		"abstract": "Since at least the 1970s, social theorists have been increasingly interested in the complex issues surrounding the construction of space and place in human activity.  Whereas previously “space was treated as static, neutral, transparent, and hence theoretically uninteresting,” many theorists have begun to explore the constructed nature of both space and place, the relationship between the two, and the relationship of both to issues of power and identity (Feld and Basso 1996; Lefebvre 1976; Soja 1980; Tuan 1977).  It is perhaps ironic that in game studies, where the spaces are more obviously constructed, little seems to have been written about the ways and ends to which players create and sustain imaginary spaces.  In this paper I explore the creation of space in Dungeons & Dragons, a case study I consider in the context of Gabbert's (2007) study of McCall, Iowa and Basso's (1996) study of the Western Apache.  Aligning these three studies allows each of them to nuance and illuminate one another, creating a complex picture of the human experience of space and place.",
