		"id": "http://zotero.org/groups/446523/items/AVIDV4W8",
		"type": "thesis",
		"abstract": "This ethnography examines the construction of a Secondary World within Live Action Role\nPlay. Based on five months of anthropological research in the United Kingdom, its aim is to\nplace LARP within the context of existing anthropology on play and performance and\nexamine how LARP constructs an alternate reality for the players. LARP is separated from\nthe mundane world by the “magic circle”, created by explicit rules and the social contract. In\ngame, players strive for immersion, similar to the concept of flow, in which players feel that\nthey are their characters. This immersion is enabled by character performance, a fully\nsensorial atmosphere, and personal relationships between the characters. Once immersed,\nplayers no longer feel as if they are acting, but rather that the character has taken over. This\nimmersion allowed players to enter the Enchanted State and an alternate reality in which\ncharacters are performative and actions within game were referred to as authentic. This adult\nplay allows players to construct a fragile alternate reality based on the belief of its players.",
