		"type": "article-journal",
		"abstract": "Games are written for different purposes: LARPs to entertain, Serious\nGames to inform and educate, and simulations as training tools or to\ndiscover how people might respond to different situations. No matter the\nreason, they all need to keep the participants actively involved and\ninterested in the scenario. A failure to maintain interest means that the\nsimulation or game fails in its purpose. Structured goal setting, as\ndescribed in Locke & Latham (2002), is proposed as a technique for\nmaintaining player focus and interest, and for putting the plot into the\nhands of the players. Relevant research is reviewed, and application\nwithin a variety of games is discussed. Suggested methods of applying\ngoal setting to simulation design are provided.",
