		"id": "http://zotero.org/groups/446523/items/RYRAKCH4",
		"type": "article-journal",
		"abstract": "A ROLE-PLAYING situation I use to teach revising strategies in business and technical writing classes helps to motivate and involve my students, who typically have considerable work experience. This article describes the role play, which concerns draft and revised versions of a memo about a fatal plane crash sent by a communications manager to her employees (Lay, Wahlstrom, Rude, Selfe, & Selzer, 1995/2000, pp. 274, 276). ROLE-PLAYING Role-playing is a well regarded learning activity (McKeachie, 2002). By participating in this activity, students can apply their knowledge through their assigned roles in a realistic but risk-free situation. The role play stimulates class discussion, dramatizes rhetorical principles about purpose, shows how to adapt a text to an audience of employees in a nonacademic setting, and allows students to reflect on their own work experience and its impact on their behavior after the role play. Students build on the knowledge of management types that they gained in courses or in their own work experience, especially the distinction between Theory X and Theory Y managers as described by Douglas McGregor (see, for example, Koontz & O'Donnell, Weihrich, 1980) and Theory Z, inspired by Ouchi (1981). The role play does not require rehearsal and uses only short scripts that are provided to the cast at the beginning of class. It also involves many students who both act out assigned parts and engage in spirited discussion. THE SITUATION Briefly, all the students pretend to work for a corporate communications manager, Jane Lilly, who wrote draft and revised versions of a fictional memo to employees at the Jeppesen Corporation (Appendixes A and B). In the first draft of the memo, she berates employees for drawing charts with the wrong scale, leading to the fatal plane crash and lawsuit that the company lost. As a result of her comments, my students, in the role of Jeppesen employees, feel that the manager has chastised and blamed them for the tragedy. In contrast, the revised memo explains court rulings and enlists the cooperation of the staff to prevent further communication failures. Carrying Out the Role Play At the beginning of class, I assign two students to read the memos aloud, three students to represent the three management styles, and one student to serve as a master of ceremonies (MC). These students face the class on a makeshift stage at the front. The managers stand by giant cards bearing the letters of their appropriate style to remind the class about who they represent. The rest of the class takes on the role of writers in the communication department at Jeppesen and vote by a show of hands on what management style Lilly uses. To begin the role play the MC says, \"Good [morning/afternoon], ladies and gentlemen. These three managers will tell you about their management styles.\" Next, Manager X says, \"I am Manager X. I use Theory X management. Workers are lazy. You have to stand over them with a stick to get them to work.\" Alter that, Manager Y says,.",
