		"type": "thesis",
		"abstract": "Dungeons & Dragons (D&D) livestreams have grown in popularity, with cast members streaming games to sizeable audiences. Because of the presence of the audience and the possibility of interactivity, there is potential for audiences to impact the narrative being told in the game. A series of interviews and first hand observations of Dungeons & Dragons livestream shows were conducted to create an understanding of current audience interactions and impacts. The results show a wide variety of ways that audience interactions profoundly impact the game’s narrative and the type of role they play in the creation of the story. This study then provides a basis for conversations around designing audience interaction to best align with the story and the collaborative narration process.",
