		"type": "chapter",
		"abstract": "From Spacewar to the persistent multiplayer worlds of the 21st century, video games have moved from subculture to mainstream industry and various genres also have emerged. Among the genres, role-playing games (RPGs) require special attention, and readers of this chapter should be familiar with the concept of role-playing. RPGs are interactive worlds where players assume the roles of fictional characters and determine their own actions based on the character they play. Players typically follow a storyline in a fictional world and interact with other player (PCs) or non-player characters (NPCs) to complete missions and achieve various goals. As the player completes quests and overcomes conflicts, his/her character advances in levels and becomes stronger. Tabletop fantasy RPGs have parallels to wargames and educational simulations, but they focus more on the role and player choices are virtually unlimited (Fine, 1983). The key difference between tabletop RPGs (or FRPs) and computer RPGs is that the video game is no longer a collectively produced fantasy and takes place within strictly defined parameters (Apperley, 2006). These games were being played in many cities in Turkey, especially in İstanbul in the mid-1990s. To make a more detailed examination of the evolution and the current state of this subculture, an analysis of the late 1990s’ FRP Cafés would be undeniably noteworthy...",
