		"type": "thesis",
		"abstract": "There are certainly exiting possibilities in examining the tabletop role-playing game in general and D&D in particular within the context of literary studies. While games, gaming and gamers make for an interesting field of study in and of itself, recent developments in game studies seems to have favored the videogame and left the tabletop role-playing game behind. This thesis will attempt to approach the tabletop role-playing game in a novel way through the context of adaptation studies. While adaptations of written literature to film generally, and of fantasy literature to fantasy film specifically, have featured more frequently in academic study, there is little to be found in relation to the adaptation of a tabletop role-playing game to film. This thesis finds its starting point in the movie Dungeons & Dragons (2000) but will also, due to the relative scarcity of previous academic writing on similar or comparable subjects, explore adaptation across the domains of roleplaying games and cinema film at a more general level.",
