		"type": "chapter",
		"abstract": "Games are, perhaps, a slightly new way of telling a story, expressing some meaning, or creating a beautiful environment. In that case, the philosophers should expect the relationship between game designer and player to map onto the familiar relationship between artist and audience. Designers hoped to create mechanics that would support collaborative storytelling, player creativity, and narrative improvisation. And the improvisations are still constrained by the rules – since players still have to follow the rules and roll for their various attempts inside the flashbacks. Those rolls create quite a bit of emergent chaos, which conditions further creativity. Players are playing to find out, to discover, how history goes – and they find those answers in their own collaborative improvisation, as guided by the directive to fit it into the bits of history that they have already previously improvised. Player-centric games typically create enormous room for player agency and creativity, and encourage rich improvisations as part of play.",
